	                the two polarization degrees of freedom of a pair of entangled
	                photons generated in a down-conversion experiment; however, the
	                discussion applies in general, regardless of the actual
	                physical realization. Two techniques are discussed, namely, a
	                tomographic reconstruction (in which the density matrix is
	                linearly related to a set of measured quantities) and a maximum
	                likelihood technique which requires numerical optimization (but
	                has the advantage of producing density matrices that are always
	                non-negative definite). In addition, a detailed error analysis
	                is presented, allowing errors in quantities derived from the
	                density matrix, such as the entropy or entanglement of
	                formation, to be estimated. Examples based on down-conversion
	                experiments are used to illustrate our results.},
